x" /></span></p>
<h1>Delaware</h1>
<h2><strong>Spot to Read: </strong><a href="https://www.bethanybeachbooks.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Bethany Beach Books</a>, Bethany Beach</h2>
<p>This independent bookshop, set a few steps off the Bethany Beach boardwalk, is open year-round—but in the summer, you can walk straight out of the store and onto the sand, beach read in hand. (The question of what exactly <em>constitutes</em> a beach read is, as ever, one we must all answer for ourselves.) [<a href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Bethany+Beach+Books/@38.5386633,-75.0576794,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m6!3m5!1s0x89b8cde6b47a3b53:0x77a1e5bb7d9cb934!8m2!3d38.5386633!4d-75.0551045!16s%2Fg%2F1tk6wt77?entry=ttu" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><strong>What to Read There:</strong></h2>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780345806406" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="119604" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literature-of-belonging-stories-of-real-america/book_unknown_americans/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/book_unknown_americans.jpg" data-orig-size="339,499" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="the book of unknown americans" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/book_unknown_americans-204x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/book_unknown_americans.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-119604 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/book_unknown_americans-204x300.jpg" alt="" width="204" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/book_unknown_americans-204x300.jpg 204w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/book_unknown_americans-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/book_unknown_americans.jpg 339w" sizes="(max-width: 204px) 100vw, 204px" /></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: left;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780345806406" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Book of Unknown Americans</em></a><br />
by Cristina Henríquez</h4>
<p style="text-align: left;">A star-crossed love story—as well as a choral portrait of the Latino immigrant experience in America—about a Mexican family who move to a Delaware apartment building. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/omPhmLoHebcEbrKE8" target="_blank">MAP</a>] <em>See also</em>: <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780393355949" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Fight Club</em></a> by Chuck Palahniuk</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781612194196" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="240505" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/debt-graeber/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/debt-graeber.jpeg" data-orig-size="265,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="debt graeber" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/debt-graeber-199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/debt-graeber.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-240505 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/debt-graeber-199x300.jpeg" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/debt-graeber-199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/debt-graeber-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/debt-graeber-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/debt-graeber.jpeg 265w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: right;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781612194196" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Debt: The First 5,000 Years</em></a><br />
by David Graeber</h4>
<p style="text-align: right;">The American anthropologist and left-wing thinker&#8217;s seminal work of economic anthropology is essential reading in the land where pretty much all American credit cards are based. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/mmSLS6eP5scjnNx36" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241525" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/quill-del/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-del.png" data-orig-size="1200,250" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="quill del" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-del-300x63.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-del.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241525" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-del.png" alt="" width="1200" height="250" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-del.png 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-del-300x63.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-del-768x160.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-del-60x13.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-del-50x10.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></h1>
<h2><strong>Poet of Note: </strong><a href="https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/alice-moore-dunbar-nelson" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Alice Moore Dunbar-Nelson</a></h2>
<p>The author of <em>Violets and Other Tales</em> and <em>Masterpieces of Negro Eloquence</em> made Wilmington her home. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/gT2gxG3azbWGauNk8" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241196" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/del/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/del.png" data-orig-size="300,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="del" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/del.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/del.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241196" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/del.png" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/del.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/del-150x150.png 150w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/del-60x60.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/del-109x109.png 109w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/del-100x100.png 100w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/del-50x50.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></p>
<h2><strong>Literary Landmark: </strong><a href="https://www.winterthur.org/exhibitions-and-collections/library/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Winterthur Library</a>, Winterthur</h2>
<p>In this 175-room house, you&#8217;ll find a host of rarities, from 17th-century atlases and European style guides to chromolithographed ephemera. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/P8qL9zBQHppCHZ8W9" target="_blank">MAP</a>]<br />
<span id="wood-thrush"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241376" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/dc-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="dc copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-300x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-1024x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-241376" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-1024x1024.jpg" alt="" width="774" height="774" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-1024x1024.jpg 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-300x300.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-150x150.jpg 150w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-768x768.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-60x60.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-109x109.jpg 109w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-100x100.jpg 100w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-600x600.jpg 600w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy-50x50.jpg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dc-copy.jpg 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 774px) 100vw, 774px" /></span></p>
<h1>District of Columbia</h1>
<h2><strong>Spot to Read: </strong><a href="https://www.busboysandpoets.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Busboys and Poets</a>, Anacostia</h2>
<p>This bright and bustling neighborhood hub manages to be bar, bookstore, brunch spot and coffeeshop, all rolled into one. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Busboys+and+Poets/@38.8662958,-76.991049,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m6!3m5!1s0x89b7b959d3085575:0xf7136b000212968b!8m2!3d38.8662958!4d-76.9888603!16s%2Fg%2F11ffm4tz6z?entry=ttu" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><strong>What to Read There:</strong></h2>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780871402103" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="31340" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/where-is-our-black-avant-garde/cane/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/cane-e1470227371522.jpg" data-orig-size="167,250" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="cane" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/cane-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/cane-e1470227371522.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-31340 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/cane-200x300.jpg" alt="Cane, Jean Toomer" width="200" height="300" /></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: left;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780871402103" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Cane</em></a><br />
by Jean Toomer</h4>
<p style="text-align: left;">A classic series of modernist vignettes that evoke Black life in urban and rural settings in the American South. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://www.google.com/maps?output=search&amp;q=logan+circle+dc&amp;entry=mc&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwiEvO_VkqX_AhU-AjQIHYzqDLwQ0pQJegQICBAB" target="_blank">MAP</a>] <em>See also: <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679767954" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Heartburn</a> </em>by Nora Ephron; <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780062193216" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Lost in the City</a> </em>by Edward P. Jones</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
