<h1>North Carolina</h1>
<h2><strong>Spot to Read: </strong><a href="https://www.malaprops.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Malaprop&#8217;s Bookstore &amp; Cafe</a>, Asheville</h2>
<p>This community bookstore spotlights and supports the work of its regional writers and is replete with cozy reading hideaways, too. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/pjvDztM4SmHTpngy5" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><strong>What to Read There:</strong></h2>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780812967586" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="240758" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/thirteen-moons/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/thirteen-moons.jpeg" data-orig-size="259,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="thirteen moons" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/thirteen-moons-194x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/thirteen-moons.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-240758 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/thirteen-moons-194x300.jpeg" alt="" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/thirteen-moons-194x300.jpeg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/thirteen-moons-39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/thirteen-moons-32x50.jpeg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/thirteen-moons.jpeg 259w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: left;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780812967586" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Thirteen Moons</em></a><br />
by Charles Frazier</h4>
<p style="text-align: left;">The author’s follow-up to <em>Cold Mountain</em>, centered on a white orphan adopted by a Cherokee chief, was translated into the Cherokee language by the Museum of the Cherokee Indian in 2007. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/KKm8ExSXVh71Psng6" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250811264" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="240757" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/soul-city-race-equality-and-the-lost-dream-of-an-american-utopia-by-thomas-healy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Soul-City-Race-Equality-and-the-Lost-Dream-of-an-American-Utopia-by-Thomas-Healy.jpeg" data-orig-size="643,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Soul City- Race, Equality, and the Lost Dream of an American Utopia by Thomas Healy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Soul-City-Race-Equality-and-the-Lost-Dream-of-an-American-Utopia-by-Thomas-Healy-193x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Soul-City-Race-Equality-and-the-Lost-Dream-of-an-American-Utopia-by-Thomas-Healy.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-240757 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Soul-City-Race-Equality-and-the-Lost-Dream-of-an-American-Utopia-by-Thomas-Healy-193x300.jpeg" alt="" width="193" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Soul-City-Race-Equality-and-the-Lost-Dream-of-an-American-Utopia-by-Thomas-Healy-193x300.jpeg 193w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Soul-City-Race-Equality-and-the-Lost-Dream-of-an-American-Utopia-by-Thomas-Healy-39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Soul-City-Race-Equality-and-the-Lost-Dream-of-an-American-Utopia-by-Thomas-Healy-32x50.jpeg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Soul-City-Race-Equality-and-the-Lost-Dream-of-an-American-Utopia-by-Thomas-Healy.jpeg 643w" sizes="(max-width: 193px) 100vw, 193px" /></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: right;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250811264" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Soul City: Race, Equality, and the Lost Dream of an American Utopia</em></a><br />
by Thomas Healy</h4>
<p style="text-align: right;">In the 1970s, Floyd McKissick dreamed of building a Black city in Warren County, North Carolina. Thomas Healy tells the tale. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/nfVh5nYdZyh96J478" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241519" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/quill-arizona/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-arizona.png" data-orig-size="1200,250" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="quill arizona" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-arizona-300x63.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-arizona.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241519" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-arizona.png" alt="" width="1200" height="250" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-arizona.png 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-arizona-300x63.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-arizona-768x160.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-arizona-60x13.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-arizona-50x10.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></h1>
<h2><strong>Poet of Note: </strong><a href="https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/george-moses-horton" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">George Moses Horton</a></h2>
<p><em>The Hope of Liberty</em> was published in 1829, transcribed from the poet’s mouth to the page by an admirer; Horton was the first Black man to publish a book in the South. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/Z28hEKbqNVDhFt2T9" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241240" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/dykeman/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dykeman.png" data-orig-size="300,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="dykeman" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dykeman.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dykeman.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241240" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dykeman.png" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dykeman.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dykeman-150x150.png 150w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dykeman-60x60.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dykeman-109x109.png 109w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dykeman-100x100.png 100w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/dykeman-50x50.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></p>
<h2><strong>Literary Landmark: </strong>Wilma Dykeman Home</h2>
<p>Dykeman&#8217;s Asheville home now hosts a Writer-in-Residence program: four weeks of quiet space where the author of <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780961385910" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Tall Woman</em></a> once worked. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/BqL2HQ34bC6mZDjw8" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
