<h2><strong>Poet of Note: </strong><a href="https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/elizabeth-woody" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Elizabeth Woody</a></h2>
<p>A Warm Springs tribal citizen, Woody is a national force as an artist and teacher, a former state laureate, and the creator of muscular, effervescent lines. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://www.google.com/maps?output=search&amp;q=warm+springs+reservation&amp;entry=mc&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwivvoKbn6X_AhW3ATQIHShWCI4Q0pQJegQIDBAB" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241244" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/powells-7/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/powells.png" data-orig-size="300,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="powells" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/powells.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/powells.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241244" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/powells.png" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/powells.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/powells-150x150.png 150w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/powells-60x60.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/powells-109x109.png 109w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/powells-100x100.png 100w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/powells-50x50.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></h2>
<h2><strong>Literary Landmark: </strong><a href="https://www.powells.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Powell&#8217;s City of Books</a>, Portland</h2>
<p>Gotta do it. Get the tote. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://www.google.com/maps?output=search&amp;q=powells+city+of+books&amp;entry=mc&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwjmvKy_n6X_AhXqJjQIHV9YCnEQ0pQJegQIDRAB" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><strong><a href="https://lithub.com/tag/Oregon/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Read more on Literary Oregon</a></strong></h2>
<p><span id="ruffed-grouse"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241476" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/pa-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/PA-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,669" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="PA copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/PA-copy-300x167.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/PA-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-241476" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/PA-copy.jpg" alt="" width="683" height="381" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/PA-copy.jpg 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/PA-copy-300x167.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/PA-copy-768x428.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/PA-copy-60x33.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/PA-copy-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 683px) 100vw, 683px" /></span></p>
<h1>Pennsylvania</h1>
<h2><strong>Spot to Read: </strong><a href="https://www.scottarboretum.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Scott Arboretum</a>, Swarthmore</h2>
<p>Swarthmore College&#8217;s 350-acre &#8220;garden of ideas&#8221; is a beautiful place to stop and read for an hour or two. Can we prove you&#8217;d be following in the footsteps of alums like Jonathan Franzen, Adam Haslett, and Norman Rush? No, but everyone likes flowers. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://www.google.com/maps?sca_esv=247eb50602a83f19&amp;output=search&amp;q=Scott+Arboretum,+Swarthmore&amp;source=lnms&amp;fbs=AEQNm0Aa4sjWe7Rqy32pFwRj0UkW1DRbm01j6DCVS0r1sTxn7h_rt6mVhwDmwtd3hPZjM8zcRGVTlPDZnJXk3Picr-AK624_I7oguu5Q8ldjEUSL4G_-MLpo6MCETap6IA7YuVw1FdAW0LTAF-gNrB9YytcGk1TLOgM4JSYTBumf_TpCimysxojSiYKvdzdomPGeDoU8LcMi&amp;entry=mc&amp;ved=1t:200715&amp;ictx=111" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><strong>What to Read There:</strong></h2>
<h4><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780449911655" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="62401" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-brief-literary-history-of-birth-control/john-updike-rabbit-run/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/John-Updike-Rabbit-Run.jpg" data-orig-size="295,500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="John Updike, Rabbit Run" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/John-Updike-Rabbit-Run-177x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/John-Updike-Rabbit-Run.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-62401 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/John-Updike-Rabbit-Run-177x300.jpg" alt="" width="177" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/John-Updike-Rabbit-Run-177x300.jpg 177w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/John-Updike-Rabbit-Run.jpg 295w" sizes="(max-width: 177px) 100vw, 177px" /></a></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: left;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780449911655" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Rabbit, Run</em></a><br />
by John Updike</h4>
<p style="text-align: left;">This classic of ennui chronicles three months in the life of Harry “Rabbit” Angstrom, a former high school basketball player in a stale town. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/eEss4BwuAW2xrfGy8" target="_blank">MAP</a>] <em>See also</em>:<a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780375701900" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em> Straight Man</em></a> by Richard Russo</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679744948" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="240785" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/a-prayer-for-the-city/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/A-Prayer-for-the-City.jpeg" data-orig-size="258,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="A Prayer for the City" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/A-Prayer-for-the-City-194x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/A-Prayer-for-the-City.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-240785 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/A-Prayer-for-the-City-194x300.jpeg" alt="" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/A-Prayer-for-the-City-194x300.jpeg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/A-Prayer-for-the-City-39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/A-Prayer-for-the-City-32x50.jpeg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/A-Prayer-for-the-City.jpeg 258w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: right;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679744948" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>A Prayer for the City</em></a><br />
by Buzz Bissinger</h4>
<p style="text-align: right;">The Pulitzer-Prize-winning journalist crafts a heartfelt epic of the idiosyncratic Philadelphia mayor Ed Rendell. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/sxWAQb1p2tANCSgV7" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241523" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/quill-ct/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct.png" data-orig-size="1200,250" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="quill ct" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct-300x63.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241523" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct.png" alt="" width="1200" height="250" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct.png 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct-300x63.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct-768x160.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct-60x13.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct-50x10.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></h1>
<h2><strong>Poet of Note: </strong><a href="https://poets.org/poet/trapeta-b-mayson" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Trapeta B. Mayson</a></h2>
<p>Mayson&#8217;s potent poems address immigration and mental health, informed by her childhood in Liberia and her work as a social worker. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/sxWAQb1p2tANCSgV7" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241246" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/psb/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/psb.png" data-orig-size="300,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="psb" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/psb.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/psb.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241246" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/psb.png" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/psb.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/psb-150x150.png 150w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/psb-60x60.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/psb-109x109.png 109w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/psb-100x100.png 100w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/psb-50x50.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></h2>
<h2><strong>Literary Landmark: </strong><a href="https://pearlsbuck.org/visit-the-pearl-s-buck-house/house/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Pearl S. Buck House</a>, Perkasie</h2>
<p>Green Hills Farm was the 67-acre homestead where Buck lived and wrote for 40 years; now, you can walk its halls and gardens. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/oBfhKnRx8zHManMaA" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
