<h1>Rhode Island</h1>
<h2><strong>Spot to Read: </strong><a href="https://jcblibrary.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">John Carter Brown Library</a>, Providence</h2>
<p>Featuring public exhibits and an indigenous languages collection, with materials sourced from the Arctic to Patagonia, the John Carter Brown Library is not to be missed. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/qBbkR732Yk3GeErS7" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><strong>What to Read There:</strong></h2>
<h4><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250849205" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="170558" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/38-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/91vmvjmrodl/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL.jpg" data-orig-size="1669,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Claire Luchette, Agatha of Little Neon" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL-668x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-170558 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL-196x300.jpg" alt="Claire Luchette, Agatha of Little Neon" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL-768x1178.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL-1001x1536.jpg 1001w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL-1335x2048.jpg 1335w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/91VMvjMrOdL.jpg 1669w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></a></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: left;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250849205" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Agatha of Little Neon</em></a><br />
by Claire Luchette</h4>
<p style="text-align: left;">When their parish is shut down, Agatha and her fellow sisters start a new life at a halfway house in the former mill town of Woonsocket. [<a href="https://www.google.com/maps?sca_esv=247eb50602a83f19&amp;output=search&amp;q=Woonsocket&amp;source=lnms&amp;fbs=AEQNm0Aa4sjWe7Rqy32pFwRj0UkW8Bt9bfRUVTzMU1CEv-WqPodRHT2B4xQ4lcpmeIYJ2nV4sm7wJq2MTCYP0L7l43VSbv_Xwi26K_NSDNpFbdEW7Hi8kRucM_U7QU8m56_M_hPYfA-HVYsNQG4beFFjQnMuc3CwfmvtLmGDf30zcfH3AXuz1VTOAWHuTh7lGbJAjUaKygvh&amp;entry=mc&amp;ved=1t:200715&amp;ictx=111" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">MAP</a>]</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780062366696" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="240786" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/dylan-goes-electric/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Dylan-Goes-Electric.jpeg" data-orig-size="278,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Dylan Goes Electric" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Dylan-Goes-Electric-209x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Dylan-Goes-Electric.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-240786 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Dylan-Goes-Electric-209x300.jpeg" alt="" width="209" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Dylan-Goes-Electric-209x300.jpeg 209w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Dylan-Goes-Electric-42x60.jpeg 42w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Dylan-Goes-Electric-35x50.jpeg 35w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Dylan-Goes-Electric.jpeg 278w" sizes="(max-width: 209px) 100vw, 209px" /></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: right;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780062366696" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Dylan Goes Electric</em></a><br />
by Elijah Wald</h4>
<p style="text-align: right;">A fascinating history of the historic night at the Newport Folk Festival when Dylan plugged his guitar into an amp and left folk music behind. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/cpXDU6v5k2cRr8uy5" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241522" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/quill-colorado/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-colorado.png" data-orig-size="1200,250" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="quill colorado" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-colorado-300x63.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-colorado.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241522" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-colorado.png" alt="" width="1200" height="250" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-colorado.png 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-colorado-300x63.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-colorado-768x160.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-colorado-60x13.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-colorado-50x10.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></h1>
<h2><strong>Poet of Note: </strong><a href="https://www.tinacane.ink/about.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Tina Cane</a></h2>
<p>Cane is the founder of the popular program Writers-in- the-Schools, RI, as well as the author of <em>The Fifth Thought</em>, <em>Body of Work</em> and more. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/y8qYLhh5EJ1MSKjx7" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241247" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/swan-4/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/swan.png" data-orig-size="300,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="swan" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/swan.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/swan.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241247" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/swan.png" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/swan.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/swan-150x150.png 150w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/swan-60x60.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/swan-109x109.png 109w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/swan-100x100.png 100w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/swan-50x50.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></h2>
<h2><strong>Literary Landmark: </strong><a href="https://swanpointcemetery.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Swan Point Cemetery</a>, Providence</h2>
<p>H.P. Lovecraft cultivated a cult following for supernatural horror tales; now, ardent fans leave unusual mementos at a gravestone that reads “I am Providence.” [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/HoRQHQwmVCq3X83E6" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><a href="https://lithub.com/tag/rhode-island/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Read more on Literary Rhode Island</a></h2>
<p><span id="carolina-wren"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241444" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/south-carolina-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/south-carolina-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,854" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="south carolina copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/south-carolina-copy-300x214.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/south-carolina-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-241444" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/south-carolina-copy.jpg" alt="" width="713" height="507" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/south-carolina-copy.jpg 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/south-carolina-copy-300x214.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/south-carolina-copy-768x547.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/south-carolina-copy-60x43.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/south-carolina-copy-50x36.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 713px) 100vw, 713px" /></span></p>
<h1>South Carolina</h1>
<h2><strong>Spot to Read: </strong>Angel Oak, Johns Island</h2>
<p>This gorgeous old tree’s epic branches create sprawling shade perfect for lounging. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/X3UFUsVfLCDEpZBu6" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h2><strong>What to Read There:</strong></h2>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781936787722" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="240787" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/edisto-by-padgett-powell/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Edisto-by-Padgett-Powell.jpeg" data-orig-size="259,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Edisto by Padgett Powell" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Edisto-by-Padgett-Powell-194x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Edisto-by-Padgett-Powell.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-240787 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Edisto-by-Padgett-Powell-194x300.jpeg" alt="" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Edisto-by-Padgett-Powell-194x300.jpeg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Edisto-by-Padgett-Powell-39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Edisto-by-Padgett-Powell-32x50.jpeg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Edisto-by-Padgett-Powell.jpeg 259w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: left;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781936787722" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Edisto</em></a><br />
by Padgett Powell</h4>
<p style="text-align: left;">In Powell&#8217;s lyrical novel, Simons Manigault comes of age on the titular Edisto, a “named but never discovered place in the South” found between Charleston and Savannah; his mother, “the Duchess,” believes he could be a prodigious writer. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/axLNZ81iDbVDoG5o6" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781938235986" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="240788" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/the-green-book-of-south-carolina/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/The-Green-Book-of-South-Carolina.jpeg" data-orig-size="703,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The Green Book of South Carolina" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/The-Green-Book-of-South-Carolina-211x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/The-Green-Book-of-South-Carolina.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-240788 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/The-Green-Book-of-South-Carolina-211x300.jpeg" alt="" width="211" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/The-Green-Book-of-South-Carolina-211x300.jpeg 211w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/The-Green-Book-of-South-Carolina-42x60.jpeg 42w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/The-Green-Book-of-South-Carolina-35x50.jpeg 35w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/The-Green-Book-of-South-Carolina.jpeg 703w" sizes="(max-width: 211px) 100vw, 211px" /></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: right;"><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781938235986" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Green Book of South Carolina</em></a><br />
by Joshua Parks</h4>
<p style="text-align: right;">Compiled by the WeGOJA Foundation (on behalf of the SC African American Heritage Commission), <em>The Green Book of South Carolina</em> is a first-of-its-kind travel guide to the most tourist-friendly destinations offering visitors avenues to discover intriguing African American history as they travel the state. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/kDCY5igFzS7bCQec6" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241523" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/quill-ct/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct.png" data-orig-size="1200,250" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="quill ct" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct-300x63.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241523" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct.png" alt="" width="1200" height="250" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct.png 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct-300x63.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct-768x160.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct-60x13.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/quill-ct-50x10.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></h1>
<h2><strong>Poet of Note: </strong><a href="https://marcusamaker.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Marcus Amaker</a></h2>
<p>Charleston’s first poet laureate is also a musician and the lead graphic designer for the music magazine <em>No Depression</em>. [<a class="waffle-rich-text-link external" href="https://goo.gl/maps/iuJGQ9RmgrvCGVpn9" target="_blank">MAP</a>]</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241443" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-literary-road-trip-across-america/amelia/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/amelia.png" data-orig-size="300,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="amelia" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/amelia.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/amelia.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241443" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/amelia.png" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/amelia.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/amelia-150x150.png 150w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/amelia-60x60.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/amelia-109x109.png 109w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/amelia-100x100.png 100w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/amelia-50x50.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></p>
<h2><strong>Literary Landmark: <a href="https://www.clarendoncountylibrary.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Harvin Clarendon County Library</a>, Manning<br />
</strong></h2>
<p>A five-foot-tall statue of Amelia Bedelia—the beloved (and literal-to-a-fault) creation of Manning-native Peggy Parish—stands outside the town library, which also hosts a yearly celebration around the author&#8217;s birthday. [<a href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Harvin+Clarendon+County+Library/@33.7259491,-80.0016091,9.11z/data=!4m6!3m5!1s0x88ff0c403acc0211:0xa395e37be2962733!8m2!3d33.6995643!4d-80.2109985!16s%2Fm%2F0j9w_4x?entry=ttu" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">MAP</a>]</p>
